{
  "text": "Bladder outlet obstruction (BOO) is caused by common disorders that result from congenital anomalies, such as bladder neck sclerosis, posterior urethral valve, urethral stricture and benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . BOO may lead to detrusor overactivity via cholinergic denervation of the detrusor muscle and subsequent acetylcholine hypersensitivity [CITATION_3] . Overactive bladder (OAB) induced by partial BOO (PBOO) is derived from an aberration in the micturition reflex, which leads to involuntary detrusor contraction of either myogenic or neurologic origin [CITATION_4] . Several studies demonstrated that the urothelium of bladder is more than a simple barrier because it actively contributes to bladder function [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
